### Attributes in C#

Attributes add metadata to code elements (classes, methods, properties, etc.) at compile time. This metadata can be queried at runtime via reflection.

### Built-in Attributes

```csharp
[Obsolete("Use NewMethod instead")]
public void OldMethod() { }

[Serializable]
public class MyClass { }

[Conditional("DEBUG")]
public void DebugMethod() { }

[Flags]
public enum Permissions { None = 0, Read = 1, Write = 2 }
```

### Creating Custom Attributes

```csharp
[AttributeUsage(AttributeTargets.Class | AttributeTargets.Method, AllowMultiple = true)]
public class AuthorAttribute : Attribute
{
    public string Name { get; }
    public string? Version { get; set; }

    public AuthorAttribute(string name)
    {
        Name = name;
    }
}

// Usage
[Author("Alice")]
[Author("Bob", Version = "2.0")]
public class SampleClass
{
    [Author("Charlie")]
    public void SampleMethod() { }
}
```

### AttributeUsage

| Parameter | Description |
|-----------|-------------|
| `AttributeTargets` | Where the attribute can be applied |
| `AllowMultiple` | Can the attribute be applied multiple times |
| `Inherited` | Is the attribute inherited by derived classes |

### Reading Attributes with Reflection

```csharp
Type type = typeof(SampleClass);

// Check if attribute exists
bool hasAttr = Attribute.IsDefined(type, typeof(AuthorAttribute));

// Get single attribute
var attr = (AuthorAttribute?)Attribute.GetCustomAttribute(type, typeof(AuthorAttribute));

// Get all attributes
var attrs = type.GetCustomAttributes<AuthorAttribute>();
foreach (var a in attrs)
    Console.WriteLine($"Author: {a.Name}, Version: {a.Version}");
```

### Common Built-in Attributes

| Attribute | Purpose |
|-----------|---------|
| `[Obsolete]` | Marks deprecated code |
| `[Serializable]` | Enables serialization |
| `[Conditional]` | Conditional compilation |
| `[Flags]` | Enum bit flags |
| `[DllImport]` | P/Invoke declarations |
| `[TestMethod]` | Unit test methods |
| `[Required]` | Validation (DataAnnotations) |
| `[JsonIgnore]` | JSON serialization exclusion |

### Attribute with Properties

```csharp
public class DisplayOrderAttribute : Attribute
{
    public int Order { get; }
    public DisplayOrderAttribute(int order) => Order = order;
}

public class Employee
{
    [DisplayOrder(1)]
    public string Name { get; set; }

    [DisplayOrder(2)]
    public int Age { get; set; }
}
```

### Attributes at Assembly Level

```csharp
[assembly: AssemblyTitle("MyApp")]
[assembly: AssemblyVersion("1.0.0.0")]
[assembly: AssemblyCompany("MyCompany")]
```

> **Key Point:** Attributes are metadata that can be read via reflection at runtime. Use `AttributeUsage` to restrict where your custom attribute can be applied. Attributes are instantiated only when queried via reflection. Common uses: validation, serialization, code analysis, testing.

### Conditional Attributes

```csharp
[Conditional("DEBUG")]
public void Log(string message)
{
    Console.WriteLine(message);
}
// Calls to Log are removed in Release builds
```

### Caller Info Attributes

```csharp
public void Log([CallerMemberName] string member = "",
                [CallerFilePath] string file = "",
                [CallerLineNumber] int line = 0)
{
    Console.WriteLine($"{file}:{line} - {member}");
}

